{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01Jgwt4UxrtaP66cvCmXJrc8","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Two NPS analogs differing in modifications. Native NPS sequence is SFRNGVGTGMKKTSFQRAKS.\n\n**PEP-57AA9A237F**: (D-Ser1)-FRNGVGTGMK-(N-Me-K12)-(N-Me-T13)-SFQRAKS-NH2\n- D-amino acid only at position 1 (Ser1 is the least critical N-terminal residue)\n- N-methylation only in mid-region (positions 12–13), outside the activity-critical 1–10 segment\n- C-terminal amidation (typically enhances stability/potency)\n\n**PEP-DCA805671F**: SF-(D-Arg3)-NGVGTGMKKTSFQRAKS\n- D-Arg in position 3 — this residue is part of the SFRNG motif that Ala/D-scan studies (Camarda et al.) identify as essential for NPSR activation; D-substitution here disrupts the key cationic side-chain orientation\n- Free carboxylate C-terminus\n\nThe N-terminal pharmacophore (positions 2–5) is the dominant determinant of NPSR potency. Disrupting Arg3 stereochemistry is far more damaging than the modifications carried by PEP-57AA9A237F, which are concentrated either at position 1 (tolerant of D-Ser) or in the less critical mid/C-terminal region, and which actually gain stability from C-terminal amidation.\n\nPrediction: PEP-57AA9A237F is the more potent agonist."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":527,"cache_read_input_tokens":26457,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":527},"output_tokens":56,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3f84bad7-e523-4313-9bd9-1e365205f696","uuid":"aac43fd2-3d91-4dcb-abdf-89fd02d2b804"}
